    //- A multi-phased feature development plan
    section.container-wrapper.margin-top48.border-top
      .container-fluid
        .row.row-no-gutters.padding-top30
          .col-md-offset-1.col-md-10.col-sm-12
            h3 A multi-phased feature development plan
        .row.row-no-gutters.padding-top30
          .col-md-offset-1.col-md-5.col-sm-12
            p Productizing add-ons would touch many parts of the 10-year-old platform, from project build to checkout, creator dashboard to transactional emails. Our feature team, Creator Tools, had a multi-phased approach to developing the feature, starting with the highest-priorities, #[span(class="bold") Checkout] and #[span(class="bold") Project Build]. 
          .col-md-5.col-sm-12
            p I was brought on board while the development of checkout with add-ons was in flux. For the next few months, I would be the sole designer for all checkout edge cases, secondary UIs, transaction emails, and most importantly, the #[span(class="bold") add-on creation flow for creators].
        .row.row-no-gutters.padding-top30
          .col-md-offset-1.col-md-10.col-sm-12
            img(src="assets/img/kickstarter/add-on-timeline.png").full

    //- Leverage quantitative data to design adaptive, resilient UIs
    section.container-wrapper.margin-top48.border-top
      .container-fluid
        .row.row-no-gutters.padding-top30
          .col-md-offset-1.col-md-10.col-sm-12
            h3 Leverage quantitative data to design adaptive, resilient UIs
        .row.row-no-gutters.padding-top30
          .col-md-offset-1.col-md-5.col-sm-12
            p Creators need a way to build and manage add-ons. Traditionally, reward building has been done in Project Build, the de-facto campaign-building part of Kickstarter. We historically had only supported 2 reward-type objects: reward and items. Add-on would be the 3rd addition to this product surface.
            p.padding-top18 Before architecting this experience, I wanted to gain a full understanding of the current UI scope. What’s the average/min/max number of rewards per launched project, sliced by categories and funding tiers? How many items does each reward have on average/at min/at max? What percentage of projects itemize their rewards? 
          .col-md-5.col-sm-12
            p I want to design an experience that is resilient to errors and edge cases, that serves the 80% case just as well as the 20% case. For a feature that deals with lots of numerical data, this is a core UX principle.
        .row.row-no-gutters.padding-top30
          .col-md-offset-1.col-md-10.col-sm-12
            img(src="assets/img/kickstarter/add-on-looker.png").full
        .row.row-no-gutters.padding-top30
          .col-md-offset-1.col-md-10.col-sm-12
            img(src="assets/img/kickstarter/add-on-ux-concepts.png").full
    
    //- Creators equate add-ons with items, not rewards
    section.container-wrapper.margin-top48.border-top
      .container-fluid
        .row.row-no-gutters.padding-top30
          .col-md-offset-1.col-md-10.col-sm-12
            h3 Leverage quantitative data to design adaptive, resilient UIs
        .row.row-no-gutters.padding-top30
          .col-md-offset-1.col-md-5.col-sm-12
            p With this feature, I placed great emphasis on rapid testing and iterations. From late April to mid-June 2020, I did a total of 3 rounds of testing and design iterations, walking through the feature with 10 creators from various funding tiers and categories, from under $5K to over $100K, games to publishing, independent to big-named creators.
          .col-md-5.col-sm-12
            p Through rapid testing, we were able to:
            +bullets(
          "Validate creators’ desire to custom assign add-ons to rewards, which was originally scoped out",
          "Uncover creators’ perception of add-ons as singular items, not entire rewards"
        )
        .row.row-no-gutters.padding-top64
          .col-md-offset-1.col-md-10.col-sm-12
            img(src="assets/img/kickstarter/add-on-item-to-add-on.png").full
            p Creators can quickly turn an item into an add-on
        .row.row-no-gutters.padding-top64
          .col-md-offset-1.col-md-10.col-sm-12
            img(src="assets/img/kickstarter/add-on-assign.gif").full
            p I worked on various interaction models for custom add-on assignment (in modals, within main reward management UI, etc.) After 3 rounds of user walkthroughs, I settled on incorporating the interaction in the add/edit flow, as it caused the least friction.
        .row.row-no-gutters.padding-top64
          .col-md-offset-1.col-md-10.col-sm-12
            img(src="assets/img/kickstarter/add-on-cell-ui-variations.png").full
            p The cell design went through many iterations. I made extensive use of iconography for edit actions and created a system for color-coded pills. The cells also had gone through a bunch of accessibility and UI pressure tests.
          
    //- Launch is not the end
    section.container-wrapper.margin-top48.border-top
      .container-fluid
        .row.row-no-gutters.padding-top30
          .col-md-offset-1.col-md-10.col-sm-12
            h3 Launch is not the end
        .row.row-no-gutters.padding-top30
          .col-md-offset-1.col-md-5.col-sm-12
            p The feature was launched in Beta to selected creators in September, 2020. Both creators and backers were excited and it shows.
            p.padding-top18 However, our work is yet finished. We know the launched product is still missing major originally scoped-in functionalities—our hope is that the beta launch would help us prioritize what to invest in. 
          .col-md-5.col-sm-12
            p Our friends from Insights have kindly helped us conduct some post-development usability tests and set up NPS surveys to collect user feedback.
